HN Digest uses Next.js (with React Email and CopilotKit), TypeScript, and Neon Postgres for the database. The frontend uses CopilotKit's `useFrontendTool` hook to handle section additions safely. Here’s a code snippet showing how a section is added:
tsx
useFrontendTool({
  name: "add_section",
  parameters: z.object({
    type: z.enum(["hn-stories", "topic", "recent-gems", "high-signal"]),
    count: z.number().min(1).max(30).optional(),
    query: z.string().optional(),
    hours: z.number().optional(),
    minPoints: z.number().optional()
  }),
  handler: async ({ type, count, query, hours, minPoints }) => {
    const section = {
      id: `${type}-${Date.now()}`,
      type,
      props: { count, query, hours, minPoints }
    };
    setConfig(prev => ({ ...prev, sections: [...prev.sections, section] }));
    return `Added ${type} section`;
  }
});

During activation, the Resend API key is encrypted using AES-256-GCM before being stored in the database. The encryption process generates a random initialization vector (IV) and an authentication tag, combining them with the ciphertext. The key is decrypted only in memory at send time, never logged or exposed to the browser. Here’s the encryption function:
ts
function encrypt(text: string): string {
  const iv = crypto.randomBytes(16);
  const cipher = crypto.createCipheriv("aes-256-gcm", getKey(), iv);
  let enc = cipher.update(text, "utf8", "hex") + cipher.final("hex");
  return `${iv.toString("hex")}:${cipher.getAuthTag().toString("hex")}:${enc}`;
}

The live preview is rendered server-side using React Email, so the preview HTML is identical to the final email. Every change in the editor triggers a request to `/api/preview`, which returns the rendered HTML. The editor caches previews by config hash to avoid re-fetching identical configurations. Here’s the caching logic:
tsx
const cacheKey = `${PREVIEW_CACHE_VERSION}:${JSON.stringify(config)}`;
const cached = previewCacheRef.current.get(cacheKey);
if (cached) { setPreviewHtml(cached); return; }
const { html } = await (await fetch("/api/preview", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
  body: JSON.stringify({ config })
})).json();
previewCacheRef.current.set(cacheKey, html);
setPreviewHtml(html);
